This program:
- Collects Terrestrial Automatic Identification System (AIS) data for ports 
  worldwide (with limitations) from https://aisstream.io/.
- Filters for Static Ship Data and Position Reports, for tankers, and removes
  invalid data.
- Determines draught events using a set of filters, DBSCAN, and a GMM.
- Calculates deadweight tonnage among other metrics and assigns classifcations 
  using MARAD categories.
- Regression estimation.
- Map loaded and unloaded product by country.

To run:
- Ensure you have an API key for aisstream.io. You need a github account to 
  register. 
- Ensure your working directory path ends in "/ais_pls".
- "source" setup.R and ensure you pass the checks.
  - You can adjust the mc.cores argument in process_2_parser_filter.R. 
- "source" background_launcher.R using source("files/background_launcher.R")
  or use the rStudio source button to execute the processes.
  - Note: this includes process_3_cpu_intensive.R running after 24 hours. If you
          don't want to wait this long, just run the program as above, and then
          source process_3_cpu_intensive.R separately after changing its timing 
          parameter. However, it is preferable to run process 3 in large batches.
          It also runs with overlap with for the past 60-84 hours for extra-long
          draught events. When calling across the processed files, ensure to 
          remove duplicates.

Notes:
- To stop sleeping from interrupting the process so that you can run this 24/7,
  you used the Amphetamine app if using a mac. Set a session to remain open as
  long as an rStudio process is running.
- There's a decent amount of uncertainty in this. The regressions used to 
  ascertain deadweight tonnage and the following metrics become less accurate 
  with each step because I have to estimate using regressions and look-up 
  tables. Additionally, it misses geographic regions around ports in Africa, 
  the Middle East, and some parts of Europe and Canada. There is probably more 
  that I'm missing too but it's good enough for now.
- When logs/processes gets really full, I just delete it and remake the folder
  (when it's not running).

Folders:
- /data
  - /raw_hex
    - Process 1 saves raw hex files from aisstream.io's websocket.
  - /filtered
    - Process 2 takes raw_hex and filters it to here.
  - /processed
    - Process 3 takes filtered data processes it to here.
    - Includes missing data and errors.
  - /output
    - Process 3 takes processed data and aggregated the final section to create
      the finished product, that is, tanker draught events without any missing 
      data.
    - A single file that is updated.
  - /tanker_mmsi_registry.rds
    - A registry of tanker MMSIs. Because we can only collect dynamic data if it
      has an MMSI associated with a tanker, this allows us to identify tankers
      before receiving the static data report, which is the document that 
      identifies a vessel as a tanker or not.
  - /regression_data.csv
    - Regression data used in dwt_estimation.R. As this collect more data, this 
      can be expanded upon and hopefully becomes more accurate. Requires manual
      lookup of dwt (gt is optional).
  - port_list.rds and port_list_2.rds
    - Relevant to port_list.R.
- /files
  - /ais_api_key.R
  - /setup.R
  - /process_1_websocket_receiver.R
    - Gets data in hex and saves quickly.
  - /process_2_parser_filter.R
    - Filters hex data for static and dynamic data, and specifically for tankers.
  - /process_3_cpu_intensive.R
    - Calculate cargo events and deadweight tonnage among other metrics.
  - /background_launcher.R
    - Launches processes 1-3.
  - /kill_process.R
    - Ready command to kill the process.
  - /dwt_estimation.R
    - Regression to estimate equation to find dwt from length.
  - /port_list.R
    - Assigns ports (process 3 does this, but this does it better, need to remove 
      this part in process 3) and maps loading and unloading by country.
- /logs
  - /error_log.txt
  - /processes 
    - Errors and messages for individual processes
- /readme.txt
- /bash_commands.txt
  - Commands I keep for when the STOP_AIS.txt call stops working, when I want 
    to run the AIS tracker in the background and still have access to R. Lots
    of kill commands.
- /seaports_of_the_world.pdf
  - PDF which lists ports and their associated coordinates.
  - To be merged with current port list.

